<body>
    <div class="form-container">
        <h2>User Feedback Form</h2>
        <form id="feedbackForm">
            <label for="name">Name:</label>
            <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required>
            <span class="error" id="nameError"></span><br>

            <label for="email">Email:</label>
            <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
            <span class="error" id="emailError"></span><br>

            <label for="feedback">Feedback:</label>
            <textarea id="feedback" name="feedback" rows="4" required></textarea>
            <span class="error" id="feedbackError"></span><br>

            <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>
        <div id="response"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('feedbackForm').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
            event.preventDefault();

            const name = document.getElementById('name').value;
            const email = document.getElementById('email').value;
            const feedback = document.getElementById('feedback').value;

            // Clear previous errors
            document.getElementById('nameError').innerText = '';
            document.getElementById('emailError').innerText = '';
            document.getElementById('feedbackError').innerText = '';

            // Validate form fields
            if (!name) {
                document.getElementById('nameError').innerText = 'Name is required';
                return;
            }

            if (!email.includes('@')) {
                document.getElementById('emailError').innerText = 'Invalid email format';
                return;
            }

            if (!feedback.trim()) {
                document.getElementById('feedbackError').innerText = 'Feedback is required';
                return;
            }

            // Send data to the server
            fetch('/submit', {
                method: 'POST',
                headers: {
                    'Content-Type': 'application/json'
                },
                body: JSON.stringify({ name, email, feedback })
            })
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(data => {
                document.getElementById('response').innerText = data.message;
            })
            .catch(error => {
                console.error('Error:', error);
                document.getElementById('response').innerText = 'There was an error submitting the form.';
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Back-End (Node.js + Express)

Next, let's set up a simple Node.js backend using Express to handle the form submissions securely.

1. **Install Node.js and npm**: Ensure you have Node.js and npm installed on your machine.

2. **Create a New Project**:
   ```sh
   mkdir form-prototype
   cd form-prototype
   npm init -y
   ```

3. **Install Dependencies**:
   ```sh
   npm install express body-parser cors
   ```

4. **Create the Server**:
   Create a file named `server.js` and add the following code:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const cors = require('cors');

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

// Middleware
app.use(bodyParser.json());
app.use(cors());

// Route to handle form submissions
app.post('/submit', (req, res) => {
    const { name, email, feedback } = req.body;

    // Basic validation on the backend
    if (!name || !email.includes('@') || !feedback.trim()) {
        return res.status(400).json({ message: 'Invalid input' });
    }

    // Log the data (for demonstration purposes)
    console.log(`Received feedback from ${name} (${email}):`);
    console.log(feedback);

    // Respond with success message
    res.json({ message: 'Feedback submitted successfully!' });
});

// Start the server
app.listen(port, () => {
    console.log(`Server running on http://localhost:${port}`);
});
```

5. **Run the Server**:
   ```sh
   node server.js
   ```

### Summary

- **Front-End**: The HTML form includes client-side validation and sends the data to the server via a POST request.
- **Back-End**: The Node.js server uses Express to handle the form submission, validate the data, and log it (or perform further actions as needed).

This setup provides a basic yet secure way to capture and process user feedback. You can expand upon this by adding more advanced security measures, such as encryption, access controls, and logging mechanisms, as described earlier.

